Ronald responded on A004; I haven't received critique from anyone
else.
 
> 1.  When you refer to the Black Repeals, please provide a brief
> explanation.  Keep in mind that not all readers of JAN will have
> played in Agora.

Ok.  (Well, I wasn't a Player then either, I just found out about
it through conversation and such.  I'll include an explanation,
though.)
 
> 2.  You write "[a meta-game solution] goes so completely against the
> grain of the ideas behind Nomic, as proposed by Peter Suber..."
> On the contrary, it seems to me that this is central to what
> Suber is exploring.  He questions whether the Rules could ever
> be made truly unchangeable, *even if* all Rule-Changing Rules
> were repealed.  In his book he includes a survey of when states
> have changed the amendment clause of their state constitutions.
> Most have done so.  Some have done so on the authority of
> the old Amendment clause.  But some have appealed to a clause
> in the preamble, which often states something to the effect that
> the people have the inherent right to revolt and throw out the
> old system.  One might argue whether this is in fact a "metagame"
> solution, since the revolt is explicitly stated in the Constitution,
> but no method is listed, and I would argue that even a peaceful
> revolution is outside of the system.

So what are you suggesting?  Just that I drop the Suber reference?

> 3.  Finally, it seems to me that the only reason you advance for
> avoiding metagame solutions is the satisfaction and pride of Agorans.
> Is there no other reason?  (If the answer is "no," then this isn't
> really something that needs to be included in your paper.  Just
> me asking.  To me, that seems a pretty poor reason to avoid
> metagame solutions, but that's just my personal opinion.)

Hmm... well, it seems to me that looking at Agora from an experimental
standpoint, one should attempt if at all possible to continue the
experiment without modification from the outside... I'll put something
to this effect in the paper.
 
> Chuck

Vanyel

