> > Playing By the Rules
> >
> > by Don "Vanyel" Blaheta
> >
> > Abstract: Although Nomic is essentially a game played by consensus
> > (like any other game), there are compelling reasons to play by the Rules
> >
> >    The game of Nomic works, like any other game, by a consensus of the
> > Players to follow the Rules set out and agreed upon at the beginning of
> > the game.  In a game of, for example, Monopoly, Players may agree on a
> > "house rule"--a variation on the Rules, agreed on by all Players, which
> > has just as much force of law as anything listed in the rulebook.
>
> I'd like to see some discussion, or at least mention, here of the
> distinction between agreeing a "house rule" at the beginning of the
> game (as is usually the case in Monopoly) and agreeing one in the
> middle (as is the case for the occasional suggestion of this sort
> made for Agora).

Hmm... yes.  I'll see what I can work out.

> >    Such a solution could solve many problems that arise in Nomic.  For
> > example, once the Black Repeals had been Proposed, voted on, and passed,
> > all the Players (or at least a majority) could have agreed that it was
> > silly to do so, and break the Rules of Nomic, temporarily, to fix the
> > problem.  Working outside of the Rules like this is always an option whi
> > is available to Players of Nomic.
>
> Some expansion on the theme that agreeing changes to the Rules in
> fact _is_ possible in Nomic without going outside the Rules, would
> be useful.  In most cases, (the Kudo problems recently being an
> example) a majority of Players can agree that the Rule should be
> changed, and can simply vote on the issue to correct it.

You're right, that emphasizes the point much more.

> > ...
> >    For there is the problem with such a `meta-solution'.  For over one a
> > a half years, Agora Nomic has continued *without a break*.  The Rules ha
> > been followed and the very same game has been continuously played since
> > then.  But, if a meta-solution had been employed, the game would not hav
> > been continuous.  It would have had a glaring discontinuity in it, much
> > as if the previous game had ended, and all involved had begun a new game
> > with an initial ruleset bearing a very strong resemblance to the Ruleset
> > as of just prior to the problem.
> I think it would be worth considering here the possibility that in
> some cases, it simply is not possible to continue within the Rules.
> There is still a vague disagreement (in certain quarters :) as to
> whether the solution to the Black Repeals really _was_ legal, and
> it is eminently possible that something could happen which really
> would eliminate the possibility to play on.

Rrm.  Well, I suppose so.  (grumble) :)

